<span id="freeTextContainer12731853855791024536">This was not a Pendergast book of note. Too much Corrie and not enought Pendergast. He&apos;s why I wait for the next in the series. Corrie pretty much annoyed me from the get go. Whiney, self-absorbed and quite stupid. There also didn&apos;t seem to be the thought, depth and layers that there normally are. I figured out who the arsonist was a quarter, maybe, of the way into the book. I realize that they can&apos;t bring back the older characters, but if Corrie is going to be a predominant character, I may dec</span>
  <span id="freeText12731853855791024536" style="display:none">This was not a Pendergast book of note. Too much Corrie and not enought Pendergast. He's why I wait for the next in the series. Corrie pretty much annoyed me from the get go. Whiney, self-absorbed and quite stupid. There also didn't seem to be the thought, depth and layers that there normally are. I figured out who the arsonist was a quarter, maybe, of the way into the book. I realize that they can't bring back the older characters, but if Corrie is going to be a predominant character, I may decide not to continue with this series. I did, however, really like the weaving of the Wilde/Conan-Doyle story. I understand that over time it becomes more and more difficult to keep a series fresh and interesting. The Pendergast series has been one of my ultimate favorites since Relic. Maybe it's time to retire Pendergast.</span>
