  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2525834964" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2525834964" />
    <a title="Lobstergirl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1910836-lobstergirl"><img alt="Lobstergirl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1380256801p2/1910836.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2525834964?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lobstergirl" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lobstergirl" href="/user/show/1910836-lobstergirl">Lobstergirl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1910836-lobstergirl?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1910836-lobstergirl?shelf=mystery-thriller">mystery-thriller</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2525834964" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18132984501892146661"><br/>I&apos;m sure you, like me, wanted to punch Pendergast in the face as the novel opened. True, he&apos;s moved on from the drug addiction and suicidal tendencies he was suffering after his wife&apos;s murder, but Pendergast&apos;s metrosexual undertaker shtick has been wearing thin for several novels. The authors stuff his refinement, if you want to call it that, down our throats. Pendergast can never be served a drink on a tray, it has to be on a <i>salver</i>. No regular-person drinks; it has to be <i>pastis</i>. Into the glass</span>
  <span id="freeText18132984501892146661" style="display:none"><br />I'm sure you, like me, wanted to punch Pendergast in the face as the novel opened. True, he's moved on from the drug addiction and suicidal tendencies he was suffering after his wife's murder, but Pendergast's metrosexual undertaker shtick has been wearing thin for several novels. The authors stuff his refinement, if you want to call it that, down our throats. Pendergast can never be served a drink on a tray, it has to be on a <i>salver</i>. No regular-person drinks; it has to be <i>pastis</i>. Into the glass of pastis he pours water from......a motherfucking <i>beaker</i>. (Is that a thing?) Quite honestly the most Joe-sixpack thing he was doing this particular day on the Côte d'Azur was reading <i>The Faerie Queene</i>.<br /><br />The actual crimes being committed here are exciting, but the whole back story is silly and boring: Oscar Wilde and Arthur Conan Doyle meeting up to chat about cannibals, the discovery of an unpublished Sherlock Holmes tale which throws light on some disinterred skeletons, an old mining town with toxic waste lurking beneath the snow drifts. Corrie Swanson is Nancy-Drewing it around town, getting arrested for desecrating graves, being stalked at her housesitting job, groped by archivists, handcuffed to pipes, chased by snowmobilers, falling down mineshafts, ignoring Pendergast's stern admonitions to <i>get out of town while she still can</i>.<br /><br />It used to be that one could construct a drinking game around the <i>susurrus</i> in a Pendergast book, but in this one there are only two. Wilde and Doyle dine at a hotel, "amid the susurrus of genteel conversation and the tinkle of cutlery...." and at a press conference, fears of arson bring about "a susurrus of muttering."</span>
  <a data-text-id="18132984501892146661" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


